\begin{abstract}
On October 11, 2019, the Czech premiere of the multimedia work \emph{Fantasia Apocalyptica}~\cite{knuth2023fantasia} took place at Masaryk University, marking the 25th anniversary of its Faculty of Informatics (\acro{FI~MU}) and featuring the composer and author Donald Knuth. The performance was recorded and later \href{https://youtu.be/wk7dEKMPP68}{published on the faculty's YouTube channel}.~\cite{fimu2020english}

In this article, written on the occasion of Knuth's 88th birthday, we describe the complete preparation of the recording, from processing the raw audio and video footage through recreating the projection panels that accompanied the performance to assembling the final master. With the exception of super-resolution enhancement, introductory and closing edits, and audio compression, the workflow relies exclusively on free and open-source tools, including \TeX, Audacity, Aegisub, \acro{FF}mpeg, \acro{MLT}, \acro{PDF}tk, and ImageMagick. The article explains how these tools can be combined into a practical, reproducible workflow that readers may apply to their own recordings.
\end{abstract}

\makeatletter
\def\@thefnmark{}\@footnotetext{This article is an expanded translation of an earlier article published in \emph{Zpravodaj}~\cite{starynovotny2024priprava}, the journal of \CSTUG.\par For further information about Knuth's visit to Brno, see also articles transcribing his public lectures~\cite{szaniszlo2020dva, szaniszlo2021two} and describing the accompanying multimedia performance~\cite{luptak2019fantasia}.}
\makeatother

\section{Introduction}

The Czech premiere of Donald Knuth's multimedia organ oratorio, \emph{Fantasia Apocalyptica}, was a notable cultural and academic event connected with several historical and institutional milestones:
\begin{description}
\item[A quarter century:] The event formed the main part of the 25th-anniversary celebrations of \acro{FI MU}; see also \url{25.fi.muni.cz}.
\item[Honoring a pioneer:] Donald Knuth is the first honorary doctor of Masaryk University, a title awarded in 1996 on the initiative of \acro{FI MU}.
\item[Institutional context:] organizing and recording the premiere reflects the faculty's long-standing association with Knuth's work and its influence on computer science and digital typography.
\item[Typographical context:] This connection is also reflected in the visual identity of \acro{FI MU}: its logo incorporates the ligature ``\acro{FI}'' and was created using Knuth's \hologo{METAFONT} system.~\cite[Figure~2]{xSojka:2017:TSJ}
\item[The work:] \emph{Fantasia Apocalyptica} is a composition based on the biblical \emph{Book of Revelation}. It combines musical structure with textual and visual elements, based on a dictionary of symbolic musical motifs~\cite{knuth2023fantasia} and accompanying imagery.
\end{description}

The rest of this article describes the open-source workflow used to turn the raw footage into a high-resolution recording. Section~\ref{sec:acquisition} covers acquisition and processing of the raw audiovisual data; Section~\ref{sec:opening-speech-and-closing-segment} the preparation of the opening speech and closing segment; Section~\ref{sec:panels} the preparation of the accompanying panels; and Section~\ref{sec:final-video-assembly} the assembly of the final recording. Finally, Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} describes the screening of the finished video at \acro{FI~MU} on December~18, 2019.

\section{Audiovisual acquisition and processing}
\label{sec:acquisition}
The video and audio of the performance were acquired and preprocessed by Pavel \v{S}iler, Petr Holub\'{a}\v{r}, and students of the \acro{LEMMA} laboratory~\cite{lemma}. We normalized the video format and mixed ambient sound and the opening speech into the audio.

\subsection{Video acquisition}
The video recording of the performance was made by Pavel \v{S}iler using a Sony~\acro{PXW-X70} camera. The footage includes Donald Knuth's lectures at \acro{FI~MU}, as well as shots of the church and organ and the opening speech by Ji\v{r}\'{i} Zlatu\v{s}ka, then dean of \acro{FI~MU}.
% Not a typo: Ji\v{r}\'{i} was then dean, not now.

\subsection{Video processing}
Although the video was acquired in a resolution of $1920\times1080$\,px at 25 frames per second (\acro{FPS}), the final recording was expected to have at least twice the resolution (\acro{4K}) and framerate (50~\acro{FPS}).

The lecture recordings were provided in a non-interlaced (progressive) format, whereas the footage of the church, organ, and opening speech was in an interlaced format. In addition, the lectures and opening speech were recorded from a tripod, in contrast to the handheld shots of the church and organ. The goal of the video processing was therefore not only to increase the resolution and framerate, but also to unify the video format and stabilize the handheld footage.
