\subsection{Text and illustration animation}
We first generated transition animations between successive images using \acro{FF}mpeg; see Figure~\ref{fig:transition}.\footnote{The variable \texttt{\$D} denotes the transition duration in seconds. We used \texttt{D=0.52} for short transitions (520\,ms) and \texttt{D=1} for long transitions (1\,s). At 50~\acro{FPS}, short transitions last 26 frames and long transitions 50 frames.}

\begin{figure}[t]
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{images/flowblade-small}
\caption{Synchronizing text and illustration panels with the audio in Flowblade.}
\label{fig:flowblade}
\end{figure}

We then synchronized the images with the audio of the performance using the free video editor Flowblade; see Figure~\ref{fig:flowblade}. We exported the Flowblade project to an \acro{XML} file in the format used by the \acro{MLT} library and extracted image timing data using the following Python~3 program:

\begin{mintedblock}
\begingroup
\small
\begin{minted}{python}
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
from pathlib import Path

images, tree = {}, ET.parse('project.xml')
for producer in tree.findall('.//producer'):
  image = Path(producer\
    .find('property[@name="resource"]').text)
  producer_id = producer.attrib['id']
  entry = tree.find('.//playlist/entry'
        f'[@producer="{producer_id}"]')
  images[image] = int(entry.attrib['out']) \
                - int(entry.attrib['in']) + 1

sorted_images = sorted(images.items())
with open('illustrations.txt', 'wt') as f1, \
     open('texts.txt', 'wt') as f2:
  for image, duration in sorted_images:
    dir = image.parent.name
    f = f1 if dir == 'illustrations' else f2
    print(f'{image.name} {duration}', file=f)
\end{minted}
\endgroup
\end{mintedblock}

For example, a line \texttt{194.png 1119} in the output file \texttt{illustrations.txt} means that the image \texttt{illustrations/194.png} (shown in Figures~\ref{fig:transition} and~\ref{fig:flowblade}) lasts 1,119 frames, i.e., about 22 seconds at 50~\acro{FPS}.

We selected transitions based on image duration: images shorter than 2 seconds are followed immediately by the next image; those 2--5 seconds long by a short transition (520\,ms); and those longer than 5 seconds by a long transition (1\,s).

We then generated a video for each image using \acro{FF}mpeg, with duration reduced by the transition time. For example:
\begingroup
\small
\begin{verbatim}
$ ffmpeg -loop 1 -framerate 50           \
>        -i illustrations/194.png        \
>        -t $(bc -l <<< '1119 / 50 - 1') \
>        -r 50 output-video-verse-21-08.mp4
\end{verbatim}
\endgroup

Finally, we concatenated the image and transition videos into three animated videos: Greek and English text, Czech text, and illustrations~\cite{ffmpeg-concat}.

