\subsection{Organ sheet music}
For each of the 22 chapters, Tom\'{a}\v{s} Szaniszlo opened digitized organ scores in a \acro{PDF} viewer and recorded the screen while scrolling the score in sync with the audio, producing 22 videos; see Figure~\ref{fig:screen3}.

We cropped the videos from 1920\,px to 1344\,px to remove side margins:
\begingroup
\small
\begin{verbatim}
$ ffmpeg -i input-video.mp4 \
>        -vf 'crop=1344:1076:280:4,
>             pad=w=1920:h=1076:x=ow-iw/2'\
>                :y=oh-ih/2:color=white   \
>          output-video.mp4
\end{verbatim}
\endgroup

We then added a white rectangle at the top of the video. Initially, it overlays the top margin; once Tom\'{a}\v{s} has scrolled down, it becomes a semi-transparent gradient:
\begingroup
\small
\begin{verbatim}
$ ffmpeg -i input-video.mp4 \
>        -vf "drawbox=0: 0:1920:62:white:fill"\
>                   ":enable='lte(n,$N)',
>             drawbox=0: 1:1920:1:white@0.983"\
>                   ":enable='gt(n,$N)',
>             ...
>             drawbox=0:61:1920:1:white@0.016"\
>                   ":enable='gt(n,$N)'" \
>          output-video.mp4
\end{verbatim}
\endgroup

The variable \texttt{\$N} denotes the frame at which the rectangle becomes semi-transparent.

We then edited and synchronized the videos in Flowblade and rendered the final output using Melt:
\begingroup
\small
\begin{verbatim}
$ melt project.xml -consumer avformat:out.mp4 \
>      vcodec=libx265 crf=17 pix_fmt=yuv420p  \
>      acodec=aac ab=384k ar=44100
\end{verbatim}
\endgroup

